Name: aje_avon
Title: Avon RB-146 Mk.302 Turbojet
Description: The Avon was Rolls-Royce's first axial-flow turbojet, introduced in 1950. The RB.146, an early 1960s model, was the ultimate military Avon, an afterburning turbojet powering the English Electric Lightning F.6. 72.77kN wet, 56.45kN dry. SFC 0.85/1.85 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.4.

Name: aje_atar
Title: Atar 9K-50 Turbojet
Description: Early 1970s afterburning turbojet, used on the Mirage 5S, Mirage 50, Mirage IV-A/P/R, and Mirage F1C. Comparitively low overall pressure ratio (6.2) leads to high fuel consumption but good high-speed performance. 70.6kN wet, 49.18kN dry. SFC 0.98/1.99 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.8.
SPACECRAFT: Mirage 5S, Mirage 50, Mirage IV-A/P/R, Mirage F1C

Name: aje_j75
Title: J75-P-17 Turbojet
Description: Essentially a larger J57, the P&W J75 saw extensive military and civilian use. This afterburning variant powered the F-106 A/B. 109.0kN wet, 76.5kN dry. SFC 0.8/2.15 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.5.

Name: aje_solarPanels
Title: ST4 Solar Panel
Description: Static Level 3 solar panel 5m^2.

Name: aje_f404
Title: F404-GE-402 Turbofan
Description: General Electric F404-GE-402 low-bypass turbofan with afterburner as used on F/A-18C/D. 78.7kN wet, 53.16kN dry. SFC 0.82/1.74 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.85.

Name: aje_j57
Title: J57-P-21 Turbojet
Description: Late 50s turbojet. The J57 was a workhorse, designed in the early 1950s and powering the B-52, most of the Century Series fighters, and even the U-2. This represents a later model, the -21, which powered the F-100C/D/F. 75.4kN wet, 45.4kN dry. SFC 0.77/2.1 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 1.9.

Name: aje_al31
Title: AL-31FM turbofan
Description: Modern afterburning turbofan used on the Su-27M, Su-30, and Su-34 featuring vector thrust.  122.4 kN wet, 76.2 kN dry, SFC 0.75/1.92 lb/lb hr. Max 2.5 Mach.

Name: aje_ramjet
Title: CR2 Ramjet
Description: A fictional CR2 Ramjet. Works best when faster than Mach 2. This engine provides no thrust below Mach 0.3!

Name: aje_j79
Title: J79-GE-17 Turbojet
Description: The first US "Mach 2" engine, the J79 saw extensive service, powering the B-58 Hustler and the F-4 Phantom and F-104 Starfighter among others. This mid-1960s model powered the USAF F-4E and G, and with minor mounting differences (as the -19) the final development of the Starfighter line, the F-104S.79.63kN wet, 52.8kN dry. SFC 0.84/1.97 lb/lbf-hr static. Temperature limit Mach 2.6.

Name: solarpaneles1
Title: AIES ES-1B Solar Panel
Description: A little over two times bigger than the ST1 plus the latest state of the art technology, the ES1B gives the user that much more capability. 0.455m^2.

Name: RO-Kestrel
Title: Kestrel Vacuum Engine
Description: Pressure-fed kerosene/LOX engine that was used in the second stage of the Falcon 1 launcher. Diameter: [1.4 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: microEngineSE1
Title: Lunar Module Ascent Engine
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Dishmccomu
Title: AIES CommTech CM-60 Dish
Description: Medium dish, useful anywhere within the inner planets. Higher bandwidth than CL-1.

Name: Dishpcf
Title: AIES CommTech PCF-5 Dish
Description: A light dish for short range communication. (PART IN PROGRESS, MAY NOT WORK)

Name: orbitaiespod
Title: AIES C1 'Orbiter'
Description: The Orbiter pod was initially of a conical design, but the early prototypes had problems with ergonomics for spaceship controls. The production version became more bulky and heavy, but at least you can operate the craft now.

Name: xluzopl
Title: AIES OPL-Lum Illuminator
Description: Small but powerful, this lighting system is quite useful in dark places. No, it's not a lamp.

Name: legstrotLandingLeg
Title: AIES Legstrot Landing Leg
Description: VHME-T is an effective landing system leaving enough space below. This development was a challenge for the AIES engineering department but we are very satisfied with the results.

Name: galaxvr2
Title: Aestus Vacuum Engine
Description: Upper stage engine of the Ariane 5ES. Burns hypergolic propellants. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: dest5Engine
Title: Generic 2kN Thruster
Description: Thruster for orbital maneuvers, similar to ones used in the Galileo probe. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Dishcl1
Title: AIES CommTech CL-1 Dish
Description: An early, small high-gain antenna. Rather wide cone and high bandwidth for Comm satellites in GEO, live video from the Moon, and similar tasks. Effective range ~37 Gm, power consumption 50 Watts.

Name: torpod
Title: AIES R350 'TOR' [1.0m]
Description: This small probe was designed to carry out very specialised government space projects, but as the market for space modules grew the 'downgraded consumer version' had to be introduced. Spy cameras are not included.

Name: moduldesspod
Title: AIES P1 'Moduldess'
Description: Previously a deep water research bathysphere (which previously was a pressure cooker) is now used for interplanetary travel. The waterproof interior has a single seat for kerbonaut and a full set of controls to operate the spacecraft. The waterproof quality is achieved by newly discovered phenomenon known as 'There is no water in space'.

Name: enginelmodc
Title: Lunar Module Descent Engine
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: investpod
Title: CubeSat Core
Description: Something so small you can throw it away and not realize it's potential.

Name: dishcomlar1
Title: AIES Comlar 1 Dish
Description: A powerful high-gain fixed dish, capable of reaching Saturn. High bandwidth.

Name: PAPBarometer
Title: AIES P.A.P. Barometer
Description: Measures the pressure of the atmosphere. Surprise!

Name: Maxurpod
Title: 702MP Satellite Bus
Description: Large Satellite Bus for your bigger satellites in orbit.

Name: VR1vulcan
Title: RS-68 Series
Description: 1990s Medium TWR atmospheric engine. Using technology developed for the Space Shuttle SSME, the RS-68 is a single-use engine, featuring a simplified design with less parts and an easier construction. The RS-68 powers the Delta IV launch vehicle family and is the most powerful LH2/LOX engine ever flown. Exhaust from the gas generator is used for roll control. Diameter: [2.43 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: solarPanelsond1
Title: AIES SON-D1 Solar Panel
Description: Slightly larger than the ST1 (1.5x) but the newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 0.33m^2.

Name: UAEcubplate
Title: GEOStar-2 Satellite Bus
Description: Used in many communications satellite the GEOStar-2 satellite bus will be perfect for your medium sized builds.

Name: rcsThrustermicrosn
Title: AIES SN-1 Micro RCS Thruster Block
Description: Low thrust and low consumption is not a downside of this RCS block. Using this system will help you avoid wasting precious RCS fuel.

Name: expendLandingLeg
Title: AIES 'Expend' Landing
Description: Small leg, just right for your lightweight probes.

Name: solarPanelsfa
Title: AIES SFA Solar panel
Description: Making things bigger only helps if you can make them more compact for launch...so fold things up. 1.8m^2.

Name: solarPanelsuncat1
Title: AIES SunCat-1B Solar Panel
Description: The newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 0.8625m^2.

Name: neptuno
Title: HS-333 Satellite Bus
Description: Satellite bus originally launched in 1972.

Name: liquidEngineorbit2
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: saltguia
Title: AIES A1 'Saltguia' Laser
Description: Superior red beam projector. Used as a reference for approximation to ground when landing, especially when the place is very dark.

Name: liquidEngineprodulVR2
Title: LR87 Booster
Description: Used in the first stage of the Titan rocket family, the LR87 is composed of two engines with separate turbomachinery integrated into one unit. The version used on Titan I burned kerosene and liquid oxygen, while Titan II through Titan IV burned storable propellants. A modified version burning liquid hydrogen was developed for the upper stages of Saturn V and Saturn IB, but the J-2 was selected instead. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: LRDecoupler
Title: AIES LR Decoupler
Description: Decoupled system safe and reliable, at least I mentioned AIES engineers

Name: Thermometermt1
Title: AIES MT-1 Thermometer
Description: This superior device is used to measure the temperature. Like you don't know.

Name: escalerar2s
Title: AIES ESCALER R2S Mobility Enhancer
Description: Compact ladder, should be positioned without anything blocking it from below so it could be extended downwards twice in size.

Name: sondex2pod
Title: Modular Common Spacecraft Bus
Description: Main Core for a satellite designed around the MCSB (Modular Common Spacecraft Bus).

Name: AIESrcsThrusrom9
Title: AIES ROM-9 RCS Thruster Block
Description: The RCS drive is necessary to maneuver spacecraft in space and allows greater control in the atmosphere.

Name: AIESrcsThrusrmt1
Title: AIES MT-1 RCS Thruster Port
Description: Linear RCS drive, best used for rotation. (This part refers to an RO RCS config that is not defined, and may not work correctly.)

Name: liquidEnginemogulmp1500
Title: RD-170 Series
Description: 1980s to present, High TWR, atmospheric booster engine. The RD-170 is the most powerful liquid rocket engine ever flown. Originally developed for the Energia launcher's boosters, the engine consists of four combustion chambers fed by a single turbopump. A modified version, the RD-171, is used on the first stage of the Zenit launch vehicle. Diameter: [3.8 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: godLandingLeg
Title: AIES GODEX-1A Landing
Description: Guaranteed not to crack on the heavyweight crafts. Warranty - one day after purchase.

Name: godLandingLeg2
Title: AIES GODEX-1B Landing Strut
Description: The same as "GODEX-1A", the only difference is the color. It's all about variety!

Name: plommsLandingLeg
Title: AIES PLOMM-S Landing
Description: Not the sturdiest landing strut, but is very compact when closed.

Name: solarPanelsfa2
Title: AIES SunCat-2B Solar Panel
Description: The newest technology and folding for compact, narrow storage for launch. 1.725m^2.

Name: novapod
Title: AIES G1 'Nova' [2.0m]
Description: This compact and reliable multi-purpose probe features the best fake tinfoil available on the market to increase its lifetime.

Name: microEngineex1sat
Title: Generic 0.5kN Thruster [0.3 m]
Description: Thruster for orbital maneuvers, similar to ones used in the Galileo probe. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: fuelTanklunderl
Title: AIES Lunder-L Fuel Tank
Description: This tank (actually a set of tanks) was created to meet the requirements of lunar and interplanetary missions. It is lightweight and efficient. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: tanktoemv2
Title: AIES MV-2 TOE Fuel Tank
Description: Made for probes and satellites of bigger-then-average sizes.

Name: tankminsond
Title: AIES 'Minsond' Micro Fuel Tank
Description: The right amount of fuel for small probes.

Name: fuelTanksuperior3
Title: AIES Superior-V3 Fuel Tank
Description: This enhanced version of "Superior-R2" gave birth to the new 'strategic' line of fuel tank designs. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTanksul
Title: AIES SUL-V1 Fuel Tank
Description: A little cousin to the Superior-V3 continues the 'strategic' line of fuel tank design. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: RCS125ra
Title: AIES RA-125 RCS Fuel
Description: This 2.5m RCS tank has the size and capacity to carry out most of the missions you throw it into. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: tankorb1
Title: AIES ORB-1 Fuel Tank
Description: A small experimental tank made to boost the payload of any space mission. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: ms1RCSTank
Title: AIES MS-1 RCS Fuel
Description: This fairly small and efficient RCS tank was designed for use with the SN-1 Micro RCS Thruster Block. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: fuelTankmr1
Title: AIES MR1 vr2 Fuel Tank
Description: The half sized cousin of the K7 tank. Thickness of the protective steel plate was increased to astonishing 1.4mm! (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: retinaGravimeter
Title: AIES Retina Gravimeter
Description: Measures the strength of gravity. Exactly what it says on the tin.

Name: tankMER1
Title: AIES MER-1 Fuel Tank
Description: This elegant fuel tank will benefit any final stage from both the aesthetic and performance perspectives. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: satpropt300FuelTank
Title: AIES T60 'SatProp' Fuel Tank
Description: After the satellite probes were designed a lot of golden tinfoil was left over. By using some metal boxes and battery parts this line of fuel tanks was created.

Name: fuelTank7k
Title: AIES K7 Fuel Tank
Description: A large tank with lots of fuel. Features "1mm Steel Plate"â„¢ to protect it from environmental hazards. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: tank1300cl
Title: AIES CL-1300 B Fuel Tank
Description: This is the upgrade CL1300, with the same characteristics of the old model will remain a cornerstone for the program AIES (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: RCSTanka5a
Title: AIES A5A RCS Fuel
Description: While developing the smaller line of RCS fuel tanks <CLASSIFIED> had brought up a topic of transportation safety. Because it was 'The Invention Day' this idea was not scrapped and the storage devices were redesigned. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: basepuntv2r10
Title: AIES V2-R11 Fairing Base
Description: Basis for protective fairings (TOP-1000, TOP-1500, TOP-2000). Not a decoupler.

Name: explonpod
Title: AS-4000 Satellite Bus
Description: Satellite bus as used in the GPS IIF Satellites.

Name: radr
Title: SNAP-19 RTG
Description: SNAP-19 as found on Pioneer and Viking spacecraft. This has a mounting bracket too.

Name: Sasdv4
Title: AIES DV4 - Advanced S.A.S
Description: A.S.A.S. module for large rockets with two pre-installed IK&K Labs 32A microprocessors!

Name: advSascr3
Title: AIES CR3 - Advanced S.A.S
Description: By using the latest breakthroughs in material compression it became possible to make the A.S.A.S. unit that is thinner than the ones of competitors.

Name: Dishomega2g
Title: AIES CommTech Omega-2G Dish
Description: Excellent as an orbital relay, or for communicating as far as Jupiter.

Name: tankMER6
Title: AIES MER-6 Fuel Tank
Description: The MER-6 - think for it as a stripped down of its elegance version of the MER-1. It sees active service again even despite the fact of its imminent replacement. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: desacopladorsat3
Title: AIES SAT-3 Decoupler
Description: This ultra-thin decoupler is used to save the precious space so important in some crafts. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: baseinstrul8
Title: AIES L8 Base Plate
Description: Useful to hold all scientific instruments, perfect for a probe core. Comes in two different shapes.

Name: basef1sond
Title: AIES F1 'Sond' Base Plate
Description: Useful to hold all scientific instruments, perfect for a probe core. Comes in two different shapes.

Name: liquidEngineconstelacion
Title: J-2X
Description: 2000s medium TWR, vacuum engine. The J-2X was intended to be used on the upper stages of Ares I and Ares V. Development continued after the cancellation of Ares, and early designs of SLS incorporated the engine, but selection of the RL10-powered Exploration Upper Stage resulted in the project being mothballed. Diameter: [3.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: topb1
Title: AIES TOP-B1 Fairing
Description: It is a type of rather small fairing, used in a new type of rocket AIES known as mini rockets.

Name: engineexper05
Title: RL60 Vacuum Engine
Description: Next generation cryogenic upper stage engine designed to replace the RL10, providing higher performance while maintaining the same installation envelope.  Also available in a lower 180kN thrust Vinci-180 model. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: top500a1ur5
Title: AIES TOP-500B Fairing
Description: Aerodynamic fairings specifically designed for use in long and narrow designs.

Name: conenoseram
Title: AIES 2.5m RAM Nose Cone
Description: Gives more pleasing appearance to the side tanks and boosters.

Name: adapterrads
Title: AIES RAD-S Adapter
Description: Light fuselage adapter. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: decouplersv05
Title: AIES SV-5 Base Decoupler
Description: Narrow version of Vector-B, probably fits only the AIES Engines. Base is installed first, engine should come in it, not the other way around. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: decoupvector
Title: AIES Vector-B Base Decoupler
Description: Will probably only fit the AIES Engines. Base is installed first, engine should come in it, not vice versa. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: desacopladorsat2
Title: AIES SAT-2 Decoupler
Description: Standard decoupler for use in V2-10R Fairing Base. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: desacopladorsat1
Title: AIES SAT-1 Decoupler
Description: Small decoupler for use in A1-RU5 Fairing Base. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: Separatormultifs
Title: AIES Multi-FS Separator
Description: Multi-FS system allows a nice, clean separation of two parts. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: strutsoportec1
Title: AIES C1 Support Strut
Description: This structural support adds some space between sections, you may find it useful in some of your designs.

Name: batteryBAEr
Title: AIES BAE-R Battery
Description: Small industrial battery, perfect for small probes and satellites.

Name: ASDecoupler
Title: AIES AS Decoupler
Description: New decoupled system allowing safe separation stages large side

Name: decouplersvblack
Title: AIES SV-5 Black Base Decoupler
Description: Narrow version of Vector-B, probably fits only the AIES Engines. Base is installed first, engine should come in it, not vice versa. (PART NOT COSTED BY RP-0 BUT IN CORRECT NODE)

Name: ALCOR_LanderCapsule
Title: ALCOR Pod(A)
Description: Advanced Landing Capsule for Orbital Rendezvous, a lander pod that actually is as lightweight as the manufacturer claims. Warranty void when subjected to atmospheric entry, sneeze, hard knocks and misplaced screwdrivers and/or wrenches. Packed full of high technology, leaving precious little space for the crew.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM46
Title: GEM 46 (Ground Ignited)
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star27H
Title: Star 27
Description: Apogee motor was developed for the Canadian Communications Research Centre's Communications Technology Satellite, and an offloaded version was qualified and flown successfully. With various propellant loadings and explosive transfer assemblies, it was used for the Broadcast Satellite Experiment, the Geostationary Meteorological Satellite, the Navigation Technology Satellite No. 2, the Global Positioning System Satellites, the P78-1 Satellite, and the Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite. Diameter: [0.68 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star30BP
Title: Star 30
Description: Total flown included in total for Star-30A. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star13B
Title: Star 13B
Description: Orbit insertion motor incorporated the lightweight case developed for the STAR 13 with the propellant and nozzle design of the earlier TE-M-516 apogee motor. The motor case was stretched 2.2 inches to provide for increased propellant loading. The motor was used to adjust orbit inclination of a satellite from a Delta launch. Diameter: [0.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star27
Title: Star 27
Description: Apogee motor was developed for the Canadian Communications Research Centre's Communications Technology Satellite, and an offloaded version was qualified and flown successfully. With various propellant loadings and explosive transfer assemblies, it was used for the Broadcast Satellite Experiment, the Geostationary Meteorological Satellite, the Navigation Technology Satellite No. 2, the Global Positioning System Satellites, the P78-1 Satellite, and the Geostationary Operational Environmental Satellite. Diameter: [0.68 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star31
Title: Star 31
Description: Antares III is the third-generation third stage for Vought Corporation's Scout launch vehicle. The design incorporates an 89-percent-solids HTPB propellant in a Kevlar(r) filament-wound case insulated with silica-filled EPDM rubber. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star37FM
Title: STAR 37
Description: The STAR 37 is a vacuum solid rocket motor, originally developed for the Surveyor lunar lander program as a braking stage. Later variants were used exclusively as apogee kick stages. Diameter: 0.93 m. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star15G
Title: STAR 15G
Description: Single STAR 15G motor, used in a variety of applications. This has a straight nozzle. Diameter: [0.38 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star17A
Title: Star 17A
Description: Apogee kick motor. Modifications: 175 mm straight section added to the Star 17. The 17A has been used for circularized orbits for the Skynet 1, NATO 1, and IMP-H & J satellites. This motor provides the high case safety factor required for this program. The TE-M-521-7 model used for several Air Force missions provides a typical safety factor with a 1.3 pound weight savings. Diameter: [0.44 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star20
Title: Star 20
Description: The lightweight, external nozzle is a composite of graphite, plastic, and steel. The consumable pyrogen igniter is actuated by two 6-second-delay electrical initiators or two SBASI zero-time-delay initiators. Diameter: [0.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Castor30A
Title: Castor 30A
Description: The CASTOR 30 is a low cost, robust, state-of-the-art upper stage motor. This development motor is nominally designed as an upper stage that can function as a second or third stage depending on the vehicle configuration. The design of the  CASTOR 30 uses all flight proven technology and materials. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM40AL
Title: GEM 40 (Air Ignited)
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM40
Title: GEM 40 (Ground Ignited)
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star3
Title: Star 3
Description: The STAR 3 motor was developed and qualified in 2003 as the Transverse Impulse Rocket System (TIRS) for the Mars Exploration Rover (MER) program for the Jet Propulsion Laboratory (JPL) in Pasadena, CA. Three TIRS motors were carried on each of the MER landers. One of the TIRS motors was fired in January 2004 to provide the impulse necessary to reduce lateral velocity of the MER Spirit lander prior to landing on the Martian surface. The motor also has applicability for spin/despin and separation systems. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Castor4
Title: Castor 4
Description: The Castor 4 was developed as the second stage of the Athena H missile and first flew in 1971. It was later adapted to replace Delta's Castor 2 boosters, increasing GTO capacity from 1593 lb (723 kg) to nearly 2000 lb (900 kg). The resulting Delta 3000-series launched in 1975 and was the first to adopt a staggered booster staging sequence. Previous Delta vehicles burned their motors in a 6-3 sequence and then jettisoned all SRMs at once. The heavier and longer-burning Castor 4 required that the ground-lit motors be jettisoned immediately after depletion to reduce dead weight. Early launches used a less efficient 5-4 sequence to reduce acceleration but returned to a 6-3 sequence after Delta was strengthened in the early 80s. Diameter: [1.02 m].

Name: KK_ATK_Star4G
Title: Star 4G
Description: This STAR motor was developed and tested in January 2000 under a NASA Goddard Space Flight Center program for a low-cost, high mass fraction orbit adjust motor for use in deploying constellations of very small satellites (nanosatellites). The first static test of the STAR 4G prototype motor was conducted 8 months after program start. The motor is designed to operate at high chamber pressure and incorporates a noneroding throat insert to maximize specific impulse. Diameter: [0.11 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star48B
Title: Star 48B
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star9
Title: Star 9
Description: The STAR 9 rocket motor was developed in 1993 on independent research and development (IR&D) funds to demonstrate a number of low-cost motor technologies. These included an integral aft polar boss/exit cone, two-dimensional carbon-carbon throat, and caseon-propellant manufacturing technique. Diameter: [0.22 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star5C
Title: Star 5C
Description: The STAR 5C rocket motor was initially designed, developed, qualified, and placed in production (1960-1963) under a contract with Martin Marietta. The STAR 5C is used to separate the second stage from the trans-stage on the Titan II missile and Titan launch vehicle. The current version was qualified for use in 1976, replacing the earlier main propellant grain with TP-H-3062. Diameter: [0.12 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Castor4A
Title: Castor 4A
Description: The Castor 4A was introduced on the first generation of Delta II launchers, the 6000-series, and offered improved thrust and specific impulse by replacing PBAA with higher energy HTPB. This, combined with a stretched first stage (the Extra-Extended Long Tank Thor) and a return to the more efficient 6-3 SRM ignition sequence, improved Delta's performance by 11% over the 3000-series. The Castor 4A was flown on the Delta II from 1989 until 1993, when it was replaced by the GEM 40. The boosters were also used on the Atlas IIAS from 1993 until 2004. Burn time 53 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star6B
Title: Star 6B
Description: The STAR 6B rocket motor was developed for spin-up and axial propulsion applications for re-entry vehicles. The design incorporates an aluminum case and a carbon-phenolic nozzle assembly. The STAR 6B was qualified in 1984 and first flew in 1985. Diameter: [0.18 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star63D
Title: Star 63D
Description: The STAR 63, as part of the PAM DII upper stage, has been flown from the Space Shuttle. The motor utilizes a head-end web and a carbon-phenolic nozzle. The case material is a Kevlar-epoxy composite, through future motors would be made using a graphiteepoxy composite. Testing of STAR 63 series motors began in 1978 with completion of the PAM DII motor qualification in 1985. The first STAR 63D flight was from the Shuttle in November 1985 to place a defense communication satellite in orbit. Diameter: [1.6 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_Star48BV
Title: Star 48BV
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: KK_ATK_GEM46AL
Title: GEM 46 (Air Ignited)
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: Mk1?Su30?Cockpit
Title: Su-30 Cockpit
Description: Sometimes you need to install stuff on the nose and have two crew. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Mk1?S39?Cockpit
Title: F-101B Voodoo Cockpit
Description: Cheap and simple cockpit.

Name: Trainer?Cockpit
Title: F-104 Starfighter Cockpit
Description: It was originally supposed to be a cutting-edge cockpit for a next-gen mk2 stealth fighter, but after years of delays, budget overruns and re-resigns, the project manager finally had enough: "Just call it something and push it on the markets!". Then we ended up with this thing.

Name: Focke-Wulf?Bearcat?Cockpit
Title: FW-190 Cockpit
Description: Take to the skies! (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: F8f?Bearcat?Cockpit
Title: F8F Bearcat Cockpit
Description: Vroom vroom vroom ^_^ (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Mk1?Mirage?Cockpit
Title: Mk1 Mirage 2000B
Description: Twin-seat fighter cockpit. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Typhoon?Cockpit
Title: Mk1 Typhoon Cockpit
Description: Check your orbital trajectory and the name of the pilot while dodging missiles. Features air intakes under the nose for more compact design. (PART NOT SUPPORTED BY RP-0 OR RO)

Name: Interceptor?Cockpit
Title: Gloster Meteor Cockpit
Description: Sometimes you need to install stuff on the nose too.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeC
Title: B9 Procedural Wing, All-Moving (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: RO-B9ProcWing-Early
Title: B9 Procedural Wing (Early)
Description: Rated for Mach 1 flight and below.

Name: RO-B9ProcAMWing-Supersonic
Title: B9 Procedural Wing, All-Moving (Supersonic)
Description: Rated for Mach 3 flight.

Name: RO-B9ProcWing-Supersonic
Title: B9 Procedural Wing (Supersonic)
Description: Rated for Mach 3 flight.

Name: RO-B9ProcCS-Supersonic
Title: B9 Procedural Control Surface (Supersonic)
Description: Rated for Mach 3 flight.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeB
Title: B9 Procedural Control Surface (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: B9_Aero_Wing_Procedural_TypeA
Title: B9 Procedural Wing (Spaceplane)
Description: Rated for LEO reentries.

Name: RO-B9ProcCS-Early
Title: B9 Procedural Control Surface (Early)
Description: Rated for Mach 1 flight and below.

Name: RO-B9ProcAMWing-Early
Title: B9 Procedural Wing, All-Moving (Early)
Description: Rated for Mach 1 flight and below.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Descent_Engine
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Descent Engine (LMDE)
Description: Deeply throttleable pressure-fed vacuum engine used for the descent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Uses storable propellants which are not subject to boiloff, but are far less efficient than hydrolox or even kerolox. The version used on J-class missions had slightly higher specific impulse (this, along with other changes, gave enough payload capacity for the rover, for example). A later variant (TR-201) was used on Delta as an upper stage engine (on Delta P series); this was a low-cost model with more restarts (4 instead of 2) and slightly higher thrust but lower efficiency and no throttling capability. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Parachute
Title: Apollo Parachutes
Description: Parachute landing systems for the Apollo CSM. Place in 3x symmetry around the Apollo Parachute Mount.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_RCSquad
Title: Apollo Service Module RCS Quad Thrusters
Description: This is the RCS Quad Thrusters for the Apollo Service Module. Place 4 pods 90 degrees apart. 2:1 O/F Ratio.

Name: bluedog_CXA_APAS_P
Title: APAS-89/95 Passive
Description: The Androgynous Peripheral Attach System series 89/95. This is the passive version of the APAS. It must work with the APAS-89/95 Active in order to secure proper docking.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_PassiveDockingMechanism
Title: Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Passive)
Description: This is the passive port for the Apollo Docking Mechanism. IT WILL ONLY WORK WITH THE Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Active). This should be placed on the top of the LEM.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Ascent_Cockpit
Title: Apollo LEM Ascent Stage
Description: The Apollo LEM Ascent Stage provides accommodations for two astronauts to ride to the surface atop the LEM Decent Stage, then return to orbit. Includes integrated fuel tanks, RCS, and communications system. Put the ascent engine on the bottom, and the passive docking port on the top.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Ascent_Engine
Title: Apollo Lunar Module Ascent Engine (LMAE)
Description: Pressure-fed engine used for the ascent module of the Apollo lunar lander. Diameter: [0.86 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_LEM_Descent_Tanks
Title: Apollo LEM Descent Stage
Description: The Apollo LEM Descent Stage contains fuel tanks, landing stability system, and recessed engine mounting point for the Apollo LEM. Also includes a vertical mobility device for Ascent Cockpit ingress and egress. Engine attach node located inside the hole in the bottom.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ServiceModule
Title: Apollo Service Module
Description: The Apollo Service Module that has a complete package of fuel, monoprop, batteries, fuel cells, and storage bays for your service module.

Name: bluedog_star48
Title: Star 48B
Description: Also known as the Payload Assistance Module (PAM) B, this kick motor was used for Delta and STS launches to add extra impulse to the payload. This is the short-nozzle version. Maximum thrust 76.11kN, burn time 85 seconds. Diameter: [1.3 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM60
Title: GEM 60
Description: The 60-inch (1.5-meter) diameter GEM 60 is used on the Delta IV in sets of two or four. When two boosters are used, both are equipped with thrust vector control (TVC). When four are used, two boosters use TVC while the other two use fixed nozzles to reduce weight. Burn time 90 seconds. Diameter: [1.52 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM46
Title: GEM 46
Description: The 46-inch (1.2-meter) diameter GEM 46 was used on the Delta III and Delta II Heavy. On both vehicles they were used in sets of nine, with six ignited at liftoff and three ignited after burnout of the first six. On the Delta III, three ground-lit boosters were equipped with thrust vector control (TVC) while all the remaining boosters used fixed nozzles. The Delta II Heavy used no boosters with TVC. Burn time 75 seconds. Diameter: [1.17 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB7segStack
Title: UA1207
Description: The UA1207 was used on the Titan IVA, which was developed to launch payloads that had been designed to fly on the Shuttle from Vandenberg. It was a 7-segment modification of the 5-segment UA1205 used on the Titan 3. Burn time 130 seconds. This is the (never flown, but proposed) inline version with 2 TVC tanks. Diameter: [3.05 m].

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB7seg
Title: UA1207
Description: The UA1207 was used on the Titan IVA, which was developed to launch payloads that had been designed to fly on the Shuttle from Vandenberg. It was a 7-segment modification of the 5-segment UA1205 used on the Titan 3. Burn time 130 seconds. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB3seg
Title: SRMU
Description: The Titan IVB Solid Rocket Motor Upgrade (SRMU, also know as the Upgraded Solid Rocket Motor or USRM), was developed with the goal of achieving a 25% increase in capacity over the Titan IVA with the UA1207 SRM. It achieved this through the use of a more energetic propellant and a 3-segment composite case that carried more fuel and weighed less than the UA1207's 7-segment steel case. Burn time 150 seconds, 3.2 m diameter. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Castor120
Title: Castor 120
Description: The Castor 120 is a medium solid booster used on the Minotaur and Athena launch vehicles. Its design was based on the TU-903, which serves as the first stage of the Peacekeeper ICBM. The standard thrust curve can be modified to produce a regressive burn that reduces maximum acceleration or a saddle-shaped profile that limits aerodynamic forces. Burn time 79 seconds. Diameter: [2.34 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_agenaAntenna
Title: Agena-D Antenna
Description: An extendible antenna for the Agena-D.

Name: bluedog_DeltaK_AJ10
Title: AJ10 Series (Advanced)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents advanced era AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Transtage as AJ10-138; similar models but back with the -118 designation were used on the Delta F and Delta K upper stages. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ParachuteMount
Title: Apollo Parachute Mount
Description: Structural adapter for Apollo parachutes and docking port. Place on top of the capsule, add parachutes in 3x symmetry. The Active Docking Mechanism goes on top. Includes a decoupler for the docking mechanism, to clear the way for the parachutes.

Name: bluedog_star20
Title: Star 20/Altair III
Description: The lightweight, external nozzle is a composite of graphite, plastic, and steel. The consumable pyrogen igniter is actuated by two 6-second-delay electrical initiators or two SBASI zero-time-delay initiators. Diameter: [0.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_star31
Title: Star 31/Antares III
Description: Antares III is the third-generation third stage for Vought Corporation's Scout launch vehicle. The design incorporates an 89-percent-solids HTPB propellant in a Kevlar(r) filament-wound case insulated with silica-filled EPDM rubber. Diameter: [0.76 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_alcyone
Title: BE-3/Alcyone
Description: Originally flown as the retrorocket in Block II Ranger probes, later used as apogee motor on Vela satellites and (in 1967) to launch Australia's first satellite. Diameter: [0.46 m].

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block5_SolarPanels
Title: Apollo Block V Solar Array
Description: Extendable sun-tracking Level 3 solar panel used for the Block V Apollo CSM. 8.05m^2. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_ServiceModule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Service Module
Description: Significant changes were made to better adapt Apollo to its new role as a crew shuttle for LEO and the Service Module was decreased in size and weight. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_MissionModule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Mission Module
Description: In order to increase the living space and mission duration of the Apollo Block III CSM. This mission module is essentially several more cubic meters of living space for the crew. Place it upside down in place of the lunar module, with docking ports on each end. Extract with the CSM after circularization. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_Capsule
Title: Apollo Block III+ Command Module
Description: Significant changes were made to better adapt Apollo to its new role as a crew shuttle for LEO, and the internal volume was modified to fit 5 crew for reentry. Be sure to bring extra living space by attaching the Mission Module to dock with after orbiting. By only using the Command Module, you will have resources for 5 crew for 72 hours. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_ServiceEngine
Title: Apollo Block III Service Engine (LMAE)
Description: With the decreased weight and LEO operation design, there was no longer a need for a large engine to power the CSM. NASA decided to reuse the successful Lunar Module Ascent Engine. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block3_HGA
Title: Apollo Block III High Gain Antenna
Description: A collapsable relay antenna consisting of four high gain dishes. Intended to be placed on the mounting bracket of the Apollo Service Engine Block III. FICTIONAL (Eyes Turned Skyward)

Name: bluedog_CXA_APAS_A_L04F
Title: APAS-89/95 Active
Description: The Androgynous Peripheral Attach System series 89/95. This is the Active version of the APAS. It must work with the APAS-89/95 Passive in order to secure proper docking.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_D3Tank
Title: Centaur-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-D Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_agenaPort
Title: Gemini Agena Target/Docking Adapter
Description: Gemini target/docking adapter used to convert an Agena-D into a Gemini Agena Target Vehicle.

Name: bluedog_agenaProbeCore
Title: Agena Avionics Package [1.5m]
Description: An early but advanced avionics module for upper stages. Carries an 11.8 kWh battery, providing control for just over 47 hr, and an omnidirectional antenna with an effective range of 1,500 km to ground stations. Capable of maintaining a pitch and roll program. Allows full control over the vessel, up to the tonnage limit (cumulative).

Name: bluedog_Centaur_Tank
Title: Centaur Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_centaur1875mAdapterFairing
Title: Centaur Interstage Fairing
Description: Interstage fairing for the bottom of the Centaur Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_centaur25mAdapterFairing
Title: Centaur Interstage Fairing Adapter
Description: Interstage fairing for the bottom of the Centaur Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaShortTank
Title: Agena Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short length fuel tank for the Agena Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_LargeRCS
Title: Centaur 3-Way Large RCS Block (69/111 N Class)
Description: Three way RCS block for the Centaur stages. Place one on each of the mounting blocks on either side of the engine mount.

Name: bluedog_agenaNoseCone
Title: Agena Nose Cone
Description: This nose cone is designed to go over the top of the Agena Docking Adapter for the Agena Target Vehicle.

Name: bluedog_Pioneer4
Title: Pioneer 4 Probe
Description: First US probe to escape Earth's gravitational pull after it flew by the Moon in 1959. The tiny spacecraft was spin-stabilised and carried a radiation experiment as well as two small photocells, which failed to trigger.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_D5Tank
Title: Centaur-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-D Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_WideTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_ShortTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short fuel tank for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_CentaurT_AdapterTank
Title: Centaur-T Fuel Tank Adapter
Description: Fuel tank adapter for the Centaur-T Upper Stage

Name: bluedog_agenaMediumTank
Title: Agena-A Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-A Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_AgenaA
Title: Agena-A/B Flight Pack
Description: Flight Pack RCS for Agena-A and BAC Model 8048/8081 engine.

Name: bluedog_agenaLongTank
Title: Agena-D Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-D Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_agenaShortTankM
Title: Agena Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short length fuel tank for the Agena Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_castorSRB
Title: Castor 1
Description: The Castor 1 was first used for a successful suborbital launch of a Scout X-1 rocket on September 2, 1960. Castor 1 stages were also used as strap-on boosters for launch vehicles using Thor first stages, including the Delta-D. Diameter: [0.79 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_redstone
Title: NAA-75-110 A-Series
Description: Used on the Redstone missile.  Designed for Ethanol/LOx (A-6) (1.5 O/F Ratio), it was later adapted to burn Hydyne/LOx (A-7) (1.73 O/F Ratio)(higher performance (12%) yet more toxic) for use in Jupiter C / Juno I.  When Redstone MRLV was adapted from Jupiter C for manned use the A7 was switched back to Ethanol, accepting slightly lower performance for lack of toxicity. Thrust Vector Control was provided by carbon thrust vanes (add the Redstone Fin / Thrust vane part in 4x symmetry), and additional attitude control was provided by actuating fins. Mass includes thrust frame. Diameter: [1.77 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Explorer1
Title: Explorer 1 Probe
Description: Explorer 1, the first satellite launched by the United States, was a very simple scientific probe of less than a dozen kilograms. It featured a cosmic ray detector and micrometeorite detectors, as well as temperature sensors. Mercury batteries provided a month of electricity for the high power transmitter and another two and a half months for the low-power transmitter.

Name: bluedog_ableEngine
Title: AJ10 Series (Early)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This is the original Vanguard second stage / Able / Delta configuration, without restart capability. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta_GEM40
Title: GEM 40
Description: The Graphite-Epoxy Motor (GEM) replaced the steel case used on earlier Castor-series boosters with a lighter composite case. The 40-inch (1-meter) diameter GEM 40 was used on the Delta II 7000-series in sets of three, four, or nine. When nine boosters were used, six were ignited at liftoff and the remaining three were ignited after burnout and jettison of the first six. Burn time: 58 seconds. Diameter: [1.02 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_atlasFairingAdapterTank
Title: Atlas Engine Adapter Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank adapter for the bottom of the Atlas Main Fuel Tank. It provides special nodes for the attachment of the LR105 Sustainer engine as well as the Booster Fairing for the LR89 Booster Engines.

Name: bluedog_atlas1LongTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank
Description: Main fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle. Be sure to attach the Atlas Engine Adapter Fuel Tank to the bottom of this tank before attaching the LR105 and the Engine Fairing.

Name: bluedog_Centaur_SmallRCS
Title: Centaur 3-Way RCS Block (69/111 N Class)
Description: Three way RCS block for the Centaur stages. Place one on each of the mounting blocks on either side of the engine mount.

Name: bluedog_atlas1ShortTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank (Short)
Description: Short fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle.

Name: bluedog_LR87_mod1
Title: LR87 Series
Description: The main engine block for the Titan II/III/IV launch vehicles, with thrust plate. 1.93 O/F Ratio.

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR101_Radial
Title: LR101 Series
Description: Pump or pressure-fed kerolox vernier engine. Used for attitude control and final velocity adjustment in the MA-x system (2x LR89 + LR105 + 2x LR101) on Atlas, and MB-x system (LR79 or RS-27 + 2xLR101) on Thor-Able / Thor-Agena / Thor-Delta / Delta. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR105
Title: LR105 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator sustainer engine used in the Atlas launch vehicle. It, like the Atlas's booster engines (LR89s) are lit on the ground, but after a bit over 2 minutes' flight the boosters are dropped and the Atlas core continues to orbit under the power of the sustainer engine (and the verniers for roll control and final adjustment). The final configuration of the LR105 (like the LR89) uses RS-27 components for increased performance. As a sustainer engine, the LR105 has relatively poor sea level specific impulse compared to most boosters, but somewhat better vacuum specific impulse--though the difference in both is nowhere near as pronounced as when comparing a booster to an upper stage engine. Diameter: [1.5 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Atlas_LR89
Title: LR89 Series
Description: Kerolox gas-generator engine that served as booster for Atlas. Late model LR89s were upgraded with RS-27 components for higher efficiency. Very similar to LR79 (this was the pure-booster variant). Diameter: [1.0 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_vanguardEngine
Title: Vanguard X-405
Description: First stage engine used on the Vanguard launch vehicle. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Pioneer1
Title: Pioneer 1 Probe
Description: The first spacecraft launched by NASA, in 1958. It was supposed to do a Moon flyby, but its rocket underperformed and it reentered the atmosphere two days after launch.

Name: bluedog_atlas1MediumTank
Title: Atlas Fuel Tank (Medium)
Description: Medium fuel tank for the Atlas launch vehicle.

Name: bluedog_star37
Title: Star 37FM
Description: The STAR 37 is a vacuum solid rocket motor, originally developed for the Surveyor lunar lander program as a braking stage. Later variants were used exclusively as apogee kick stages. Diameter: 0.93 m. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_explorer7probe
Title: Explorer 7 Probe
Description: A 1959 satellite designed to measure fluxes of solar x-rays, hydrogen spectral lines and cosmic rays, as well as collect micrometeorite impact data.

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Rubis
Title: P0.68
Description: 3rd stage of Diamant rockets. This is the somewhat larger version used in B and BP4 variants. Diameter: [0.80 m].

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Topaze
Title: P2.2 (Topaze)
Description: Second stage of Diamant-A and -B rockets. Four vectorable nozzles provided roll control as well. Diameter: [0.85 m].

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Rita
Title: P4 (Rita 1)
Description: French solid motor, used in a submarine-launched missile and flown as the second stage of Diamant-BP4 rockets in 1975. Diameter: [1.50 m].

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRBseparator
Title: Titan SRM separation motor
Description: Lower separation motor for Titan solids.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB5segStack
Title: UA1205
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. This is the (never flown, but proposed) inline version with two TVC tanks. Diameter: [3.05 m].

Name: bluedog_Diamant_Asterix
Title: Asterix Probe
Description: France's first satellite attained orbit in 1965. It was originally designated A-1, but later renamed after the popular comic character.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ServiceEngine
Title: AJ10-137 (Service Propulsion System)
Description: The Aerojet AJ10-137 rocket engine used on the Apollo Service Module as the Service Propulsion System. Diameter: [2.6 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_ActiveDockingMechanism
Title: Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Active)
Description: Once soft docking is achieved and the vessels properly aligned, retract the probe to hard dock and establish a solid connection. IT WILL ONLY WORK WITH THE Apollo 0.625m Docking Mechanism (Passive).

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Heatshield
Title: Apollo 2.5m Heat Shield
Description: Large 2.5m structural heatshield for Apollo CSM. It is very thick in order to withstand the intense heat of lunar reentries. Remove some of the ablator for low orbital missions, to save weight. The structure itself is lighter as well, at the cost of removing the jettison hardware. Make sure your parachutes can stop the weight of the capsule and the heatshield.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Capsule
Title: Apollo Command Module
Description: The module that was used to transport astronauts to the Moon. Room for three crew.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_Decoupler
Title: Apollo Command/Service Module Decoupler
Description: This is used to decouple the Command Module from the Service Module prior to reentry.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_DockingLight
Title: Apollo EVA / Docking Light
Description: This light (traditionally mounted to the decoupler ring on the Apollo CSM) swings out to provide illumination for docking/berthing operations and to aid astronauts on EVAs.

Name: bluedog_Apollo_Block2_HGA
Title: Apollo High Gain Antenna
Description: A collapsable relay antenna consisting of four high gain dishes. Intended to be placed on the mounting bracket of the Apollo Service Engine.

Name: bluedog_Titan_SRB5seg
Title: UA1205
Description: Strap-on booster for Titan IIIC, IIID, IIIE, proposed for Saturn IB derivatives. Burn time 115s. Diameter: [3.05 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Soltan_Inline
Title: 100-Inch SRM (inline)
Description: Inline version of the 3-segment motor designed for a solid-augmented Titan II around 1961. Four test firings were made, of which two ended with the nozzle disintegrating. Burn time roughly 80 seconds. Diameter: [2.54 m].

Name: bluedog_LR91_mod1
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_LR91_mod2
Title: LR91 Series
Description: The LR91 powered the second stage of Titan launchers. Exhaust from the gas generator provided roll control. Diameter: [2.9 m]. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_agenaLongWhiteTank
Title: Agena-B Fuel Tank
Description: Fuel tank for the Agena-B Upper Stage.

Name: bluedog_rangerCore
Title: Ranger Block I Core
Description: Probe core used for early Ranger missions as well as (in stripped-down form)  the first Mariner missions.

Name: bluedog_ablestarEngine
Title: AJ10 Series (Mid)
Description: Small pressure-fed hypergolic upper stage engine. Derivative of the first US liquid rocket engine, the AJ10 series is perhaps the longest-lived of any engine series, a part of the US's first satellite launch vehicle, Vanguard, the Apollo CSM, and even one projected Orion service module. This represents mid-period AJ10s with a nozzle extension and restart capability. Used on Thor-Ablestar and Delta E through Delta N. Plume configured by RealPlume.

Name: bluedog_Delta2_RS27

The H-1/RS-27 are optimized for the first-stage main engine role. The RS-27A has a higher expansion ratio for increased performance at altitude since liftoff thrust on the Delta II is augmented by solid boosters and the core burns rather longer. Diameter: [1.0 m]. Using the patented SSTU Engine-Clustering technology the number of engines, engine layout, mounting or shroud type, and mount/shroud size are configurable, and each set of engines are built to your specifications. Plume configured by RealPlume.
